# Trick.elm — WORKHORSE (the Trick/Play types)

Data contract for the trick plugin system. Every individual
trick (DirectPlay, PairPeel, etc.) produces values of these
types; the Hint engine collects them.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE. Tiny, stable.
- **Go counterpart ripped 2026-04-20** (`project_hints_are_client_side.md`).
  This is now the single source of truth for the trick plugin
  contract.

## Key exports

- `Trick` — `{ id, description, findPlays }`. The plugin
  itself. Stateless.
- `Play` — `{ trickId, handCards, apply }`. A concrete
  proposed move.

## `Play.apply` contract

`apply : List CardStack -> (List CardStack, List HandCard)`

Given the current board, return (newBoard,
cardsActuallyConsumed). Important:

- **Empty `cardsActuallyConsumed` means refusal.** The apply
  ran but the board drifted since `findPlays` was called —
  e.g., the target stack moved or changed. Caller treats this
  as "this play is no longer valid, drop it."
- Non-empty `cardsActuallyConsumed` means success; the new
  board is authoritative.

This preserves the invariant that tricks validate at apply
time, not just at findPlays time.

## Why Play doesn't back-reference Trick

Elm type aliases can't be mutually recursive without
indirection. Downstream consumers only need `trickId` (the
stable string like `"direct_play"`) for logging / annotation
/ fixture matching — not the full Trick record. The
back-reference would add indirection without benefit.

## `findPlays` signature

`findPlays : List HandCard -> List CardStack -> List Play`

Stateless. Run it against the current (hand, board); it
returns every applicable Play. Order matters for the Hint
engine's priority ranking (see `Tricks/Hint.claude`).

## Pointers

- Consumers: every `Tricks/*` module; `Tricks.Hint` collects
  from all of them.
